# electron-updater / electron-builder publish configuration
# ----------------------------------------------------------
#
# When you run `npm run dist` (from electron/), electron-builder
# publishes the built app to a GitHub Release. To do that it
# needs a GitHub Personal Access Token (PAT).
#
# HOW TO GET THE TOKEN
# -------------------
# 1. Go to https://github.com/settings/tokens?type=beta
# 2. Click "Generate new token" (fine-grained).
# 3. Resource owner: just you (dawei7).
# 4. Repository access: select ONLY the `code_n` repo (NOT all
#    repos — least privilege).
# 5. Permissions: `Contents: read and write` ONLY.
#    (electron-builder uses the GitHub Releases API, which lives
#    under Contents. Nothing else is needed.)
# 6. Set an expiration. 90 days is fine; rotate.
# 7. Generate, then COPY the token (you'll only see it once).
#
# WHERE TO PUT IT
# ---------------
# Paste the token into this file as `GH_TOKEN=ghp_...` and SAVE.
# This file is gitignored. NEVER commit it. NEVER paste the token
# into a chat, an issue, a wiki, or any other public surface.
#
# ALTERNATIVES
# ------------
# - Set it as a per-shell env var:    `export GH_TOKEN=ghp_...`
#   (PowerShell:  $env:GH_TOKEN='ghp_...')
# - Use Windows Credential Manager + `wincred` helper.
# - If you only ever build on one machine, the .env file is fine.
#   If you build on multiple machines, prefer the shell env var
#   so the secret never sits on disk.
#
# WHEN THE BUILD USES IT
# ----------------------
# `npm run dist`  -> electron-builder reads $GH_TOKEN from the
#   environment, uses it to create a draft GitHub Release, uploads
#   the .exe + .blockmap + latest.yml to it, and publishes.
# `npm run dist:dry`  -> same as `dist` but with --publish never,
#   so NO token is needed and nothing is uploaded. Use this to
#   sanity-check the build before doing a real release.

# Windows code signing
# --------------------
#
# Unsigned Windows installers usually trigger SmartScreen warnings.
# To make Windows show a verified publisher and build download
# reputation over time, sign each release with an Authenticode
# code-signing certificate.
#
# Standard PFX certificate flow:
#
# WIN_CSC_LINK=C:\path\to\certificate.pfx
# WIN_CSC_KEY_PASSWORD=your-pfx-password
#
# You can also use the generic electron-builder names:
#
# CSC_LINK=C:\path\to\certificate.pfx
# CSC_KEY_PASSWORD=your-pfx-password
#
# Once signing is configured, make releases fail if signing is missing:
#
# CODEN_REQUIRE_CODE_SIGNING=1
